        Chart Update 28/07/2023

        'bout time the chart answered my prayers about how static they are

        ANYWAYS. The chart. Uploaded on time. Brilliant. And with it, comes an absolute shedload of stories, ready to fill up the next few paragraphs, whilst everybody else sees more -1s than my average ratio uploading these. Starting, however, with the biggest NON-story of the week, and Dave & Central Cee.. are.. zzzzz. AAAH. SORRY THERE. I just fell asleep because it was so predictable. But yeah, 8 weeks now, biggest UK rap song of all time, can I go home now?

        Oh wait. I'm already at home. And O-Rod is STILL NO.2. The four weeks she's spent here feel like four months, it's that gutpounding. Either she tops the chart, or I do. Or, perhaps, one of the Barbie songs.

        Yeah, Barbie happened. There's more hits relating to this topic than a UFC combatant and a punching bag. We could be here all day talking about some of the stuff here, but suffice to say, the streams have taken off. So that's why Billie Eilish is up to 3rd spot withWhat Was I Made For, Dua Lipa finally breaks into the upper regions withDance The Night, and who could forget Nicki Minaj and Ice Spice doing everything they can to turn your ears into brattenburg. And that's just the tip of the iceberg.

        Out of the 7 new hits and 1 re-entry, 3 of them have quite obvious links to the hot new thing of 2023. Charli XCX grabs her first Top 20 hit since Brexit was relevant in the form ofSpeed Drive(5.6/10), which is fine when it's not racing to the finish line at 2 minutes long, Lizzo firing her way back into the 40 withPink(5/10), which, sadly, I have already forgot about since listening to the chart show. You may have also forgotten that yes, celebs CAN sing, and Ryan Gosling is here to prove it. Even if his attempt comes in the form of a pretty tame ballad (5/10). But just remember, no matter how many people ridicule you, repeat to yourself, 'I'm Just Ken'. I can guarantee you the enjoyment levels will soar when you say that.

        In other news, Jung Kook is a 1-week wonder, as expected, Becky Hill starts her (well-deserved) regular assault on the upper reaches, but most importantly, BYRON MESSIA GOT PLAYED ON RADIO 1. It only took 8 weeks and a Burna Boy remix, but a jump up to No.12 means that for the first time ever, casual listeners can be engrossed in the predictable afrobeats sound that plagues Burna Boy's other hits. I'm not dissing him or anything, but that's just how it is.

        Stormzy makes his return after the quick in-n-out form of Toxic Trait, by grabbing RAYE by the coattails and forcing her to remind us that she was on a DBE song once. Albeit a good one, but still.The Weekendis fine, the lyrics are fine, the melody is fine, but you know what's her fine. Her being up for a Mercury. Great on her I suppose, but my money is on either Fred Again, Jessie Ware, or the Arctics winning it. I was a bit sickened at the sight of The 1975's latest collection not being up for it, but that has less to do with the music and more about how Matty Healy's brain works. It's that old Morgan Wallen situation, isn't it.

        In other news, Travis Scott has a new album out now, and with it comes a song with The Weeknd on it, so you knew it'd be here. On the plus side,K-POPisn't that bad, but on the negative, is has the musical stain that is Bad Bunny, so that kinda evens itself out (5/10).

        Also helped by an unecessary remix is Noah Kanah, who rereleased her album Stick Season because A) I guess he got bored, and B),Dial Drunkwent big on TikTok. It did not make the Top 40 however, so here comes Post Malone to throw his hat in the ring and force it up to 32. An alright song and all, but I can't help feeling this song is just a little tryhard. Still, it's certainly better than some of the other country stars out there (5.5/10).

        It may have also come to your attention that Zayn Malik still has a music career. Currently he is battling to be the 3rd most popular 1D man after Harry and Niall, and given none of the stuff from his last album, Nobody is Listening (how ironic) made the Top 40, I guess you could considerLove Like This(4.4/10) a return to form. Even though he'll fall so far away from the Top 40 next week, you'll be convinced his legs are made of gravel.

        Sam Smith, Ava Max and The Kid LAROI's Barbie contributions are also in the chart somewhere, Leigh-Anne Pinnock still can't get anywhere, Beebadoobee and Ice Spice also have new songs dabbing their way in, but there is other news. Blur have yet another chart topping album, in the form ofThe Ballad of Darren, although none of the songs are on the chart. Lead singleThe Narcissistmade it to 81 a few months ago, which is a bit loserish until you realize that no songs from Blur had made the chart in over a decade. Oh, and Aqua are back at 40 withBarbie Girl. That says it all, really. What do you want me to say about this song that hasn't been said already? Apart from, this is Nicki Minaj's fault?

        But yeah, what a week. Finally the charts are getting a sense of craziness back. Hopefully next week will be of similar qualities, once Drake and Central Cee's latest freestyle stops banging on the door. G'day.


        (P.S. Sinead O'Connor has also taken off on Spotify, and with it seemsNothing Compares 2 Ure-enter at 45. I never really liked her stuff, but I respect her stuff, I wish her family some love, and I always had a soft forSpecial Casesby Massive Attack, orIllegal Attacksby Ian Brown. Bless ya Irish hart.

        H
